<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,153,1295]" pageId="6" pageNumber="307">
Scutal chaetotaxy: 1 postpronotal, 2 notopleural, 1 postsutural dorsocentral, 2 long postalar bristles. Scutum usually shiny. Scutellum convex, shiny. Subscutellum convex, microtomentose. Thoracic pleurites shiny, bare except for katepisternal bristle, setulae on katepisternum and posterior half of anepisternum; katepisternum with stronger setae near ventral margin. Wing broad, anal area and alula well-developed (
<figureCitation box="[992,1060,261,287]" captionStart="FIGURES 8–10" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1966,1991]" captionTargetBox="[165,1422,166,1933]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[165,1422,166,1946]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 8–10. Female Paraleucopis. 8, Paraleucopis saguaro sp. nov., habitus; 9, P. saguaro sp. nov., wing; 10, P. corvina, postabdomen, dorsal view. Abbreviation: tg—tergite. Scale bars = 0.5 mm, except Fig. 10 where scale bar = 0.25 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3449458" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3449458/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="307">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
); veins white or yellow; 1 anteroventral seta proximal to costagial break and 1 seta on tegula; Sc incomplete, ending just before C, not fused with R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1428,1436,314,328]" fontSize="6" pageId="6" pageNumber="307">1</subScript>
distally; C short spinose beyond R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[530,538,350,364]" fontSize="6" pageId="6" pageNumber="307">1</subScript>
; R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[571,597,350,364]" fontSize="6" pageId="6" pageNumber="307">4+5</subScript>
and M 
<subScript attach="left" box="[673,681,350,364]" fontSize="6" pageId="6" pageNumber="307">1</subScript>
converging distally; CuA+CuP (anal vein) long and straight, ending before wing margin; outstanding marginal setulae between apices of R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[941,967,386,400]" fontSize="6" pageId="6" pageNumber="307">4+5</subScript>
and M 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1046,1054,386,400]" fontSize="6" pageId="6" pageNumber="307">1</subScript>
apparently absent. Halter pale.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,153,1295]" pageId="6" pageNumber="307">
Abdomen short, broad, tergites 1 and 2 and anterior part of tergite 3 densely microtomentose, rest of abdomen shiny; tergites 1 and 2 separated dorsally by distinct transverse suture. Tergites 1–5 with short, sparse setae and long dark lateral marginal setae; sternites 1–5 quadrate, narrow, with sparse setae. Male sternite 5 entire or with narrow posterior region divided by membranous region from rest of sternite. Spiracles 
<quantity box="[1028,1098,512,539]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.62" metricValueMax="12.7" metricValueMin="2.54" pageId="6" pageNumber="307" unit="in" value="3.0" valueMax="5.0" valueMin="1.0">1–5 in</quantity>
pleural membrane near lateral margin of tergites.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,153,1295]" pageId="6" pageNumber="307">
Male postabdomen: tergite 6 relatively broad, dorsal, slightly asymmetrical; sternite 6 large, asymmetrical, ventral and left lateral. Sixth spiracles in pleural membrane near lateral margins of tergite 6. Tergite 
<quantity box="[1297,1342,621,647]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.778" pageId="6" pageNumber="307" unit="in" value="7.0">7 in</quantity>
form of long, narrow strip on right side of postabdomen; sternite 7 large, asymmetrical, on left side posterior to sternite 6, narrower dorsally. Sternite 8 asymmetrical, as broad as sternites 6 and 7 combined (
<figureCitation box="[1100,1185,693,720]" captionStart="FIGURES 45–48" captionStartId="20.[151,264,1778,1803]" captionTargetBox="[157,1427,249,1733]" captionTargetId="figure@20.[151,1436,237,1759]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURES 45–48. Male terminalia and male postabdomen of Paraleucopis spp. 45, P. nigra sp. nov., male terminalia, lateral view; 46, P. paraboydensis sp. nov., postabdomen, ventral view; 47, P. paraboydensis sp. nov., male terminalia, lateral view; 48, P. paraboydensis sp. nov., male terminalia, ventral view. Abbreviations: st—sternite; sur—surstylus; tg—tergite. Scale bars = 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3449496" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3449496/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="307">Fig. 46</figureCitation>
). Epandrium rounded, evenly sclerotized, setose. Hypandrium broader along anterior margin. Surstylus articulated with epandrium, long, narrow. Subepandrial sclerite dark, narrow. Phallapodeme short, straight; phallic guide forming narrow ventral plate, not attached to hypandrium. Pregonite long, apparently fused with hypandrium laterally. Postgonite short, posteroventrally directed, articulated with pregonite. Basiphallus with sclerotization interrupted posteriorly; distiphallus long, bare, transversely striated, with long, narrow, lateral sclerites. Ejaculatory apodeme reduced; ejaculatory duct unmodified.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,153,1295]" pageId="6" pageNumber="307">
Female postabdomen (
<figureCitation box="[448,530,945,971]" captionStart="FIGURES 8–10" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1966,1991]" captionTargetBox="[165,1422,166,1933]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[165,1422,166,1946]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 8–10. Female Paraleucopis. 8, Paraleucopis saguaro sp. nov., habitus; 9, P. saguaro sp. nov., wing; 10, P. corvina, postabdomen, dorsal view. Abbreviation: tg—tergite. Scale bars = 0.5 mm, except Fig. 10 where scale bar = 0.25 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3449458" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3449458/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="307">Fig. 10</figureCitation>
): tergite 6 long, roughly quadrate, constricted medially; sternite 6 largely desclerotized, reduced to 2 small anterior sclerites and posterior setae (see 
<bibRefCitation author="Steyskal, G. C." box="[876,1032,981,1007]" pageId="6" pageNumber="307" pagination="1 - 4" refId="ref16717" refString="Steyskal, G. C. (1971) The genus Paraleucopis Malloch (Diptera: Chamaemyiidae), with one new species. Entomological News, 82, 1 - 4." type="journal article" year="1971">Steyskal 1971</bibRefCitation>
, fig. 6). Spermathecae 2, sclerotized, clavate, denticulate; third spermatheca rudimentary. Ventral receptacle small, rounded (
<figureCitation box="[1110,1193,1017,1043]" captionStart="FIGURES 37–42" captionStartId="17.[151,264,1793,1818]" captionTargetBox="[160,1424,196,1739]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[151,1436,181,1773]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURES 37–42. Male terminalia, spermathecae and female tergite 6 of Paraleucopis spp. 37, P. corvina, male terminalia, lateral view; 38, P. corvina, female tergite 6, dorsal view; 39, P. corvina, spermathecae; 40, P. mexicana, male terminalia, lateral view; 41, P. mexicana, spermathecae and ventral receptacle; 42, P. mexicana, female tergite 6, dorsal view. Abbreviations: v rep—ventral receptacle. Scale bars = 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3449488" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3449488/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="307">Fig. 41</figureCitation>
). Cercus elongate and slender.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="307" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,153,1295]" pageId="6" pageNumber="307">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1089,1115]" pageId="6" pageNumber="307">Remarks.</emphasis>
The monophyly of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Malloch" authorityYear="1913" box="[545,694,1089,1115]" class="Insecta" family="Chamaemyiidae" genus="Paraleucopis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="307" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[545,694,1089,1115]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="307">Paraleucopis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is supported by the following synapomorphies: gena broad, anal angle of wing broad, wing veins white, costa spinose, ejaculatory apodeme greatly reduced. The illustration of the wing of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Malloch" authorityYear="1913" box="[244,486,1161,1187]" class="Insecta" family="Chamaemyiidae" genus="Paraleucopis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="307" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="corvina">
<emphasis box="[244,486,1161,1187]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="307">Paraleucopis corvina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is incorrect in 
<bibRefCitation author="McAlpine, J. F." box="[651,840,1161,1187]" pageId="6" pageNumber="307" pagination="965 - 971" refId="ref16394" refString="McAlpine, J. F. (1987) Chamaemyiidae. In: McAlpine, J. F., Peterson, B. V., Shewell, G. E., Teskey, H. J., Vockeroth, J. R. &amp; Wood, D. M. (Eds.), Manual of Nearctic Diptera. Volume 2. Agriculture Canada Monograph, 28, 965 - 971." type="journal article" year="1987">McAlpine (1987</bibRefCitation>
, fig. 10) and in other publications where this figure is reproduced. The Sc ends abruptly prior to a preapical expansion of R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[924,932,1214,1228]" fontSize="6" pageId="6" pageNumber="307">1</subScript>
and not complete as drawn (see 
<figureCitation box="[1298,1365,1197,1223]" captionStart="FIGURES 8–10" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1966,1991]" captionTargetBox="[165,1422,166,1933]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[165,1422,166,1946]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 8–10. Female Paraleucopis. 8, Paraleucopis saguaro sp. nov., habitus; 9, P. saguaro sp. nov., wing; 10, P. corvina, postabdomen, dorsal view. Abbreviation: tg—tergite. Scale bars = 0.5 mm, except Fig. 10 where scale bar = 0.25 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3449458" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3449458/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="307">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,153,1295]" pageId="6" pageNumber="307">
The genus occurs primarily in the southwestern 
<collectingCountry box="[730,882,1233,1259]" name="United States of America" pageId="6" pageNumber="307">United States</collectingCountry>
, northwestern 
<collectingCountry box="[1044,1130,1233,1259]" name="Mexico" pageId="6" pageNumber="307">Mexico</collectingCountry>
(including 
<collectingRegion box="[1256,1428,1233,1260]" country="Mexico" name="Baja California" pageId="6" pageNumber="307">Baja California</collectingRegion>
) and northern regions of 
<collectingCountry box="[419,530,1269,1295]" name="Argentina" pageId="6" pageNumber="307">Argentina</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[585,649,1269,1295]" name="Chile" pageId="6" pageNumber="307">Chile</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
